Yes. For this Type field it’s a **single-select** dropdown (`multiple` is not set), and the clear control calls `onChange` with **`null`**.

```258:260:App/Elements/Dropdown/index.js
  const onClearPress = () => {
    onChange(multiple || isArrayResults ? [] : null);
  };
```

`FormDropdown` forwards that straight into react-hook-form and your handler:

```59:63:App/Components/Forms/FormDropdown.js
        onChange={(values, item) => {
          setFieldValue(values);
          if (onChange) {
            onChange(values, item);
          }
        }}
```

So when the user taps clear on Type, **`onSelectArea` runs with `categoryId === null`** (falsy), which matches your `if (!categoryId)` branch. Using **`null`** also matches your later `if (categoryId)` guard before `getCategories`, so you don’t call the API with a bad id.

**Caveat:** the parameter is **`null` on clear**, not necessarily `undefined`; both are handled by `!categoryId`.

[REDACTED]

